Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take effect for the purpose of preserving evidence;
- to provide for the sale of any goods which are the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement and are of a perishable nature or are likely to deteriorate;
- to secure the amount in dispute in the arbitration;
- to restrain any party to the arbitration agreement from alienating any assets, or from creating any charge or lien over any assets, which are the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to secure the amount in dispute in the arbitration;
- such other interim measure of protection as may appear to the court to be just and convenient.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Under Section 10 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, specific performance of a contract can be enforced when the following conditions are met:

1. The contract is in writing (Section 10(a));
2. The contract is registered, if registration is required by law (Section 10(b));
3. The contract is of the nature for which specific performance is allowed under the Act (Section 10(c));
4. The plaintiff has performed or is ready and willing to perform his part of the contract (Section 10(d));
5. The defendant has failed to perform his part of the contract (implied);
6. The contract is not one which can be adequately compensated by damages (Section 10(e) and Section 21 of the Act, which lists contracts that cannot be specifically enforced).

Specifically, Section 10 states that except as otherwise provided in the Act, a contract can be specifically enforced when it is in writing and registered (if required), and the plaintiff has performed or is ready to perform his part of the contract.

A perpetual injunction is granted under Section 38 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, when the court is satisfied that the plaintiff has a prima facie case and it is necessary to prevent a breach of an obligation or a wrongful act that would cause irreparable injury to the plaintiff. 

Specifically, it is granted when:

1. The plaintiff has a legal right (Section 38(a));
2. The defendant has invaded or threatened to invade that right (Section 38(b));
3. The invasion or threatened invasion is such that the plaintiff is entitled to prevent or compel it by means of an injunction (Section 38(c));
4. The plaintiff has no other adequate remedy (Section 38(d));
5. The balance of convenience is in favor of granting the injunction (Section 38(e));
6. The court deems it fit to exercise its discretion in granting the injunction (Section 38).

The court may grant a perpetual injunction to restrain the defendant from doing a particular act that would cause harm to the plaintiff.

Under Section 6 of the Transfer of Property Act, 1882, the following kinds of property cannot be transferred:

1. The interest of a lessee under a lease of immovable property (Section 6(a));
2. The interest of a tenant under a tenancy agreement, where the tenant has no right to assign or sublet (Section 6(b));
3. An interest in a property that is held on behalf of another, such as a trust property (Section 6(c));
4. A mere right to sue (Section 6(d));
5. A right to future maintenance (Section 6(e));
6. A mere right to the proceeds of a decree or order (Section 6(f));
7. Any other interest in property that is not capable of being transferred (Section 6(g)).

These types of properties are not transferable as they are either not absolute or are subject to certain restrictions and conditions.

Under Section 2(68) of the Companies Act, 2013, a private company is defined as a company that has a minimum paid-up share capital of ₹1 lakh or such higher paid-up share capital as may be prescribed, and which by its articles:

1. restricts the right to transfer its shares;
2. except in the case of One Person Company, limits the number of its members to two hundred;
3. prohibits any invitation to the public to subscribe for any securities of the company.

(Section 2(68) of the Companies Act, 2013)

Under Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, the following orders are appealable:

1. Refusing to refer the parties to arbitration under Section 8 (Order refusing reference to arbitration);
2. Granting or refusing to grant any interim measure under Section 9 (Interim measures by Court);
3. Refusing to enforce a foreign award under Section 36 (Enforcement of foreign awards), after the award has become enforceable under Section 57 (Conditions for enforcement of foreign awards) or has been recognized as enforceable under Section 58 (Conditions for recognition of foreign awards);
4. Setting aside or refusing to set aside an arbitral award under Section 34 (Application for setting aside arbitral award).

These orders are appealable to the Court as per Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996.

Under Section 19 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, the following residence orders are available:

1. Restraining the respondent from dispossessing or in any other manner disturbing the possession of the shared household (Section 19(a));
2. Directing the respondent to remove himself from the shared household (Section 19(b));
3. Restraining the respondent or any of his relatives from entering any portion of the shared household in which the petitioner resides (Section 19(c));
4. Restraining the respondent from alienating any assets in the shared household (Section 19(d));
5. Directing the respondent to secure same level of alternative accommodation for the petitioner (Section 19(e)).

These orders aim to provide protection to the victim of domestic violence and ensure her right to residence in the shared household.

Under Section 5 of the Protection of Children from Sexual Offences (POCSO) Act, 2012, penetrative sexual assault becomes aggravated in certain circumstances. 

According to Section 5 (m) to (x) of the POCSO Act, penetrative sexual assault is considered aggravated when it is committed by a person in a position of authority or trust, or when it causes grievous hurt or injury, or when the child is below 12 years of age, among other circumstances.

Specifically, Section 5 of the POCSO Act states that penetrative sexual assault is aggravated when:

- The offender is a relative of the child (Section 5(m));
- The offender is a person in a position of authority or trust (Section 5(n));
- The offender is a member of the security forces (Section 5(o));
- The offender is a public servant (Section 5(p));
- The child has a mental or physical disability (Section 5(q));
- The offender has previously been convicted of an offence under this Act (Section 5(r));
- The offender commits the offence in a manner that causes grievous hurt or injury to the child (Section 5(s));
- The offender makes the child pregnant (Section 5(t));
- The offender infects the child with HIV or any other life-threatening disease (Section 5(u));
- The offender uses a deadly weapon during the commission of the offence (Section 5(v));
- The offence is committed during a natural calamity or in any similar situation of crisis (Section 5(w));
- The child is below 12 years of age (Section 5(x)).
